{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491137"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:34:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:34:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"841"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/841"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.03,0.07,0.12,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"841"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112934"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/841"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"841"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94966"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"2072"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46442"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112934"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with haematemesis. Endoscopy reveals a bleeding 10mm duodenal ulcer, which is successfully treated with endoscopic adrenaline injection and thermal therapy. A biopsy of the antrum shows numerous flagellate organisms and the rapid urease test is positive. The patient is started on esomeprazole, clarithromycin and amoxicillin for 14 days. There is no further bleeding and the patient is discharged home three days after his admission. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No follow-up required","Endoscopic re-assessment in one week","Endoscopy and re-biopsy of the ulcer in two weeks","Helicobacter pylori serology at four weeks","Urea breath test at six weeks"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patients duodenal ulcer is secondary to Helicobacter pylori infection. Provided the patient remains symptom-free, all that is required is to ensure that there has been eradication of H. pylori The most convenient way for this to be done is with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eurea breath test at six weeks \u003C/strong\u003Eafter completion of treatment. If the result is negative, this would allow the esomeprazole to be ceased as long as there are no other risk factors for peptic ulcer disease (eg. aspirin/NSAIDs).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerology\u003C/strong\u003E is likely to remain positive for several months, even after successful eradication of H.pylori, and therefore is of no clinical benefit to confirm success of H. pylori eradication therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic assessment\u003C/strong\u003E would only be required if the bleeding continued or if the patient\u0027s symptoms persisted. Another indication might be if it was thought that the ulcer could be malignant. As this is a duodenal ulcer, it is most unlikely that it would be malignant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no clear evidence in the literature that any endoscopic follow-up is required for this scenario if the patient remains well and the H. pylori has been eradicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Helicobacter pylori and NSAIDs are responsible for the large majority of cases of peptic ulcer disease."],"references":["Lanas A, Chan FKL. Peptic ulcer disease. Lancet. 2017 Aug 5;390(10094):613-624.","Therapeutic Guidelines. Helicobacter pylori infection. In: Gastrointestinal. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Gastrointestinal\u0026topicfile=c_GIG_Gastro-oesophageal-reflux-in-adultstopic_1\u0026guidelinename=auto\u0026sectionId=c_GIG_Helicobacter-pylori-infectiontopic_2","Tarasconi A, Coccolini F, Biffl WL, et al. Perforated and bleeding peptic ulcer: WSES guidelines. World J Emerg Surg. 2020 Jan 7:15:3."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94966"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"841"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94966"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T12:26:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T12:27:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"841"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112934"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attrib